2026-06-08 | Delete Nodes Having Greater Value on Right

	Question
Return the modified linked list.
	Key Insight
In a singly linked list,
looking to the right is difficult.
So:
		reverse the list
Now nodes originally on the right
appear on the left.
Traverse reversed list while maintaining:
		maxValueSeen
If current node is smaller than maxValueSeen:
		delete it
Otherwise:
		keep it and update maxValueSeen
Finally reverse the list again.
	Approach
1.	Reverse the linked list.
2.	Maintain:
		maxNodeValue
3.	Traverse reversed list.
4.	If current node value < maxNodeValue:
		remove node.
5.	Otherwise:
		update maxNodeValue.
6.	Reverse the list again.
7.	Return new head.
	Time Complexity
	O(n)
	Space Complexity
	O(1)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    Node* reverseList(Node* head) {
        Node* prev = nullptr;
        Node* curr = head;
        while(curr) {
            Node* nextNode = curr->next;
            curr->next = prev;
            prev = curr;
            curr = nextNode;
        }
        return prev;
    }
    Node* compute(Node* head) {
        head = reverseList(head);
        int mx = head->data;
        Node* curr = head;
        while(curr && curr->next) {
            if(curr->next->data < mx) {
                Node* temp = curr->next;
                curr->next = temp->next;
                delete temp;
            }
            else {
                curr = curr->next;
                mx = curr->data;
            }
        }
        return reverseList(head);
    }
};
	Key Insight
After reversing the list:
		"greater node on the right"
becomes
		"greater node already seen on the left"
This allows us to maintain a running maximum and delete unwanted nodes in a single traversal, giving an O(n) solution.
